</p></div>
<div class="solution"><p><a knowl="./knowls/solution.MINM.M20.knowl">Solution</a></p></div>
</div><div class="exercise" acro="MINM.M80">
<h5 class="exercise">
<span class="type">Exercise</span> <span class="acro">MINM.M80</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.markhamrick.knowl">Mark Hamrick</a></span>
</h5>
<div class="problem"><p>Matrix multiplication interacts nicely with many operations.  But not always with transforming a matrix to reduced row-echelon form.  Suppose that $A$ is an $m\times n$ matrix and $B$ is an $n\times p$ matrix.  Let $P$ be a matrix that is row-equivalent to $A$ and in reduced row-echelon form, $Q$ be a matrix that is row-equivalent to $B$ and in reduced row-echelon form, and let $R$ be a matrix that is row-equivalent to $AB$ and in reduced row-echelon form.  Is $PQ=R$?  (In other words, with nonstandard notation, is $\text{rref}(A)\text{rref}(B)=\text{rref}(AB)$?)<br><br>
Construct a counterexample to show that, in general, this statement is false.  Then find a large class of matrices where if $A$ and $B$ are in the class, then the statement is true.
</p></div>
<div class="solution"><p><a knowl="./knowls/solution.MINM.M80.knowl">Solution</a></p></div>
</div><div class="exercise" acro="MINM.T10">
<h5 class="exercise">
