</h5>
<div class="problem"><p>Suppose that $Q$ and $P$ are unitary matrices of size $n$.  Prove that $QP$ is a unitary matrix.
</p></div>
</div><div class="exercise" acro="MINM.T11">
<h5 class="exercise">
<span class="type">Exercise</span> <span class="acro">MINM.T11</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.robertbeezer.knowl">Robert Beezer</a></span>
</h5>
<div class="problem"><p>Prove that Hermitian matrices (<a class="knowl" acro="HM" type="Definition" title="Hermitian Matrix" knowl="./knowls/definition.HM.knowl">Definition HM</a>) have real entries on the diagonal.  More precisely, suppose that $A$ is a Hermitian matrix of size $n$.  Then $\matrixentry{A}{ii}\in\real{\null}$, $1\leq i\leq n$.
</p></div>
</div><div class="exercise" acro="MINM.T12">
<h5 class="exercise">
<span class="type">Exercise</span> <span class="acro">MINM.T12</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.robertbeezer.knowl">Robert Beezer</a></span>
</h5>
<div class="problem"><p>Suppose that we are checking if a square matrix of size $n$ is unitary.  Show that a straightforward application of <a class="knowl" acro="CUMOS" type="Theorem" title="Columns of Unitary Matrices are Orthonormal Sets" knowl="./knowls/theorem.CUMOS.knowl">Theorem CUMOS</a> requires the computation of $n^2$ inner products when the matrix is unitary, and fewer when the matrix is not orthogonal.  Then show that this maximum number of inner products can be reduced to $\frac{1}{2}n(n+1)$ in light of <a class="knowl" acro="IPAC" type="Theorem" title="Inner Product is Anti-Commutative" knowl="./knowls/theorem.IPAC.knowl">Theorem IPAC</a>.
</p></div>
</div><div class="exercise" acro="MINM.T25">
<h5 class="exercise">
<span class="type">Exercise</span> <span class="acro">MINM.T25</span> <span class="contributor"><a knowl="./knowls/contributor.manleyperkel.knowl">Manley Perkel</a></span>
</h5>
<div class="problem"><p>The notation $A^k$ means a repeated matrix product between $k$ copies of the square matrix $A$.
<ol>
<li>Assume $A$ is an $n\times n$ matrix where $A^2=\zeromatrix$ (which does not imply that $A=\zeromatrix$.)  Prove that $I_n-A$ is invertible by showing that $I_n+A$ is an inverse of $I_n-A$.</li>
<li>Assume that $A$ is an $n\times n$ matrix where $A^3=\zeromatrix$.  Prove that $I_n-A$ is invertible.</li>
<li>Form a general theorem based on your observations from parts (1) and (2) and provide a proof.</li>
</ol>
</p></div>
</div>
